There seems to be continued downward pressure on the Euro/USD exchange rate - Europe is still deep in its energy crisis. On the flipside, the dollar continues to strengthen against all other currencies - especially since the Fed has been much more aggressive about raising interest rates than the European central bank. Europe does not seem to have seen peak inflation yet, and inflationary pressures seem higher than in the US where the inflation rate has dropped two months in a row, and is scheduled to drop again in October.

Given that the euro hit parity for the first time in 20 years in July 2022, the base case of this historically happening is pretty low. However, the parity was caused by high energy prices and record inflation, which are both shifting daily. In fact, the US is actively working towards counteracting inflationary pressures, albeit difficult to say if doing so successfully. Since hitting parity in July, the euro has decreased in value, currently at 0.9847 to the dollar. In the last five days, the Euro has fluctuated up and down between slightly over 1 to below 1. Given this, I think there is a slightly less than 50-50 chance of the Euro closing at above the dollar. October is still days away, though. And the forecast is worth updating frequently.

I think it will be lower than 1.00 for different reasons:

For the last 10 years, the Euro has never fallen as far as where it is currently (1 EUR = 0.996 USD). Europe is projected to experience a crunch on its energy bills, which will cause high inflation as people spend more to stay warm as we transition into winter. America, on the other hand, doesn't look "great" when it comes to inflation but looks an awful better than Europe (especially regarding overall economic outlook). I think 35% make sense here.

The exchange rate dropping below 1 is unprecedented, and I don't know how Euro governments will react to improve their economic conditions. High energy prices in the eurozone and improving American economic conditions make me think that this downward trend will stabilize at around below 1.00, but not necessarily accelerate.

From Graphical Analysis, it seems there is a some what hard barrier for EUR to hit back USD without bouncing down. The 1-week chart shows a clear downward trend, following a longterm (primary) downward trend. But the margins are very very straight, this question must be updated every two days to get a closer response because the margin for that is incredibly narrow.

Looking at trends in the exchange rate over the past year, I notice a marked downward trend in the Euro's value relative to the dollar. Combined with projected interest hikes from the Federal Reserve, which would attract foreign investors to seek U.S. Treasuries and push up the price of the dollar even further, I think this trend will continue.

I will update my prediction however at the end of September, once I have a better understanding of the entire month's trend.

The dollar has been tightening in relation to the Euro so I think it's more likely that the rate is under 1, and we also need to account for the possibility that the two will be at complete par with each other.

My prior is that the US dollar is normally worth less than the euro. However, I did a quick Google search and read an article that says "professional investors don’t expect [the dollar] to ease off anytime soon." Additionally, I different article mentioned that the strength of the dollar is attributable to a few factors: U.S. Federal Reserve’s campaign to raise interest rates and gas prices (in Europe and in U.S.). My understanding is that the U.S. intends to keep their interest rate increase and also maintain gas prices. So I believe there is just a chance the closing value of the euro to US dollar exchange rate be higher than 1.00 on 7 October 2022.

Although the euro to US dollar exchange rate has been revolving around 1.0 since August, it has consistently been above 1.00 in the past 5 years. Given that I don’t have more information on how the war in Ukraine is going to evolve, I choose to base my forecast on historical trends

The situation in Europe continues to be complicated. Russia has suspended gas supplies through its main pipeline to Europe (Nordstream 1) and the winter is approaching. European countries face the risk to impose energy quotas on companies if gas supplies are not re-established. Other suppliers cannot cover Europe's needs swiftly given obvious infrastructure needs to do so. In addition, the Fed is likely to continue its aggressive rate hikes to quell inflation. These and other factors will continue to put significant pressure on the euro, which is quite likely to remain at or below parity with the US dollar (interpeting 1EUR will be worth less than 1USD).

In the last year the exchange rate has fallen from roughly 1.17 to almost exactly 1 today. In the last month this has fluctuated above and below 1.0. October 7 is 18 days away, meaning there is time for potentially significant adjustment. The euro has not sustained below 1 USD since 2000/2001. In the next 18 days, the energy crisis will continue and price pressure will on consumers and businesses will sustain or grow. The European countries are also figuring out their winter energy plans, which may include shutting down some industry which would potentially weaken the Euro. Thus I'll say that it will likely be lower than 1 USD by Oct 7, though with low confidence.

It's been over 20 years since the Euro and Dollar were at parity. However, the war in Ukraine and Europe's reliance on Russian oil/natural gas is driving the cost of energy up and causing inflation, depreciating the value of the Euro. Consistent, recent news reports indicate that the energy crisis won't be going away and will get worse as the weather cools down. The weather won't change too much in the next two weeks but increased uncertainty in the Ukraine-Russia conflict has my initial forecast as more likely for Euro to US exchange rate to be less than 1.

Very close call, but 3 weeks does not seem to be enough time for the euro to stay consistently below 1.00 USD. The Euro has been steadily declining across 2022, and high energy costs + rising inflation has only exacerbated this. With the US' rising interest rates, it puts even more stress and pressure on the exchange rate and value of the euro. However, the euro keeps rising and dipping at a unique rate. With Liz Truss in the UK now, her policies promote lowering energy costs and lowering inflation rates, which would help the exchange rate. In addition, with the war in Ukraine seemingly slowing down, gas prices are lowering at a gradual rate again. None of this seems like it will have an IMMEDIATE impact in 3 weeks. The price of the euro is unpredictable, but based on previous trends, I predict that the Euro will stay about 1.00 USD in the exchange rate. In 2-3 months, the euro exchange rate would be extremely interesting due to the volatility of the euro right now.

This is a hard one. The value for the last month is definitely counter to what one would predict based on the last 5 years of data. BUT, if one looks at just the last year and especially the last month, it would suggest the value will more than 1euro to 1USD. So, for three weeks from now, I expect it to be more than 1 Euro to 1 USD, a return to mean will take more than three weeks....

7 Oct 2022 is roughly three weeks away. Futures markets are pricing the EUR/USD at 1.0043 in three weeks (source: https://www.fxempire.com/currencies/eur-usd/forward-rates). That suggests markets are more confident than not that the EUR/USD will be above parity on 7 October. Over the last year, the daily volatility of the EUR/USD has been on average 0.00868 (source: https://marketmilk.babypips.com/symbols/EURUSD/volatility). I roughly estimated a three week volatility from the daily volatility, then used that to determine the PR(EUR/USD<1 in 3 weeks) assuming daily returns are normally distributed (which in financial markets is a common but incorrect assumption!)

In the past 3 weeks, the euro to US dollar exchange rate has been higher than 1.00 on 11 of those days. According to Bloomberg, the rate is currently at 1.0016. Given this data, I assigned this a 50% probability.

Very close call. The Euro is hovering right around a dollar this week. With such a short time frame, I think it is very close to a toss-up. What’s making my (very) slight tip positively: 1) Russia closing gas to Europe may have caused fear dipping the rate below 1.0, Europe’s positive responses may increase it in the coming weeks; 2) the outside view of number of days below 1.0 is very small; 3) the outside view of trend decreases at the rate we’ve seen since April is very rare since the year 2000.

The Euro has declined steadily in 2022. Currency analyst predict it will continue to fall. The rising interest rate in the US will also place downward pressure on the exchange rate. Over the past week the rate has bounce up to 1.02, so given the short period for this question I'll go with a 37% chance of the euro to dollar exchange rate being above 1.00 on 7 Oct.

Looming winter energy cost and supply and geopolitics keep dollar strong and Euro down. I think if it is below 1, it is near 1, perhaps 0.95-0.99 to 1.10. The timeframe is short - 20 days or so from today. I am feeling more optimistic in the short-term.

When I looked at the exchange rate for each day for the past month, the exchange rate has right around $1.00. The fluctuations are typically 1 cent and the most I saw within the last month were a 2 cent difference. Typically, the exchange rates that were not $1.00 were $1.01. Then I looked at the exchange rate over the past year. A year ago the exchange rate was $1. 16. There has been a steady decrease. Therefore with a steady decrease, I think that those days that were $1.01 have a good chance in a few weeks of being $1.00. Obviously there is no guaranteeing that the exchange rate is going to be exactly one dollar but it will almost certainly be around it. When looking at the probability that it is $1.00, I predict that it is 3:1 odds therefore I put 75% chance.

Euro will have to do with at least a weary winter and 2023 where energy prices are through the roof, thanks to the Russia pipeline fallout bc of the Ukraine conflict. The general EU stance has been stubborn rhetoric but not forceful or meaningful resistance to the Russian strong arm tactic to choke off a large part of its current energy supply.
